As an introverted creative, being independent and placing great value on one's privacy should not be a contradiction, but sometimes it is. Most online sources and coaches advise working with the (evil) tech giants and behaving extrovertly. Advertise here, follow the algorithm, show your personality. Get a blue tick on that service, be available 24/7, answer questions with a video of yourself, respond immediately. Video, video, video.
1/3
For me, it's a year of changes.
I don't want to feed the tech giants with money, data, and my energy. Or coaches who have their own extroverted solution and push it on everyone. I'm looking for new ways to run my business and at the same time fighting against my long-held belief that one must do something in a certain way to be successful.
Wish me luck!
I have already taken the first steps.
I have cancelled my FB account, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
Yesterday, I also removed Google Analytics, the last external tracker, from my website and feel good about it.
Recently, I subscribed to a European CRM to have better DSGVO support, and I will be moving my business there in the next few weeks.
I have transferred my MX account to Proton and now have full SPF, DKIM, and DMARC without having to pay Google for a normal email validation.
3/3
